{
  "cells": [
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "---\n",
        "title: 'Chapter 9. Linear Approximation, Tangent Planes, and Differentials'\n",
        "subtitle: 'The local linear model behind tangent planes, sensitivity, and uncertainty'\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Chapter overview\n",
        "\n",
        "The central message of this chapter is simple and powerful:\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-important title='Core principle'}\n",
        "A differentiable multivariable function is approximately linear near a point.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "In single-variable calculus, the tangent line is the best first-order approximation to a curve near a point. In multivariable calculus, the same idea becomes the **tangent plane** for a graph $z=f(x,y)$ and the **tangent hyperplane** for a function of many variables. Algebraically, the approximation is built from partial derivatives. Geometrically, it is the flat object that best matches the surface near the point. Computationally, it is the first local model used in numerical methods, optimization, uncertainty propagation, and statistical approximation.\n",
        "\n",
        "This chapter is one of the main bridges from Calculus III to graduate-level applied mathematics, statistics, data science, AI, and machine learning. Linear approximation is the mathematical idea behind sensitivity analysis, local regression, the delta method, Newton-type algorithms, first-order optimization, and the local behavior of loss functions.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-note title='Teaching-material connection'}\n",
        "This chapter develops the MATH 2321 material on tangent planes, linearization, differential approximation, differentiability, total differentials, and tangent planes to level surfaces. It uses the examples $z=3x^2+y^2$, gradient-based approximation, and the level-surface problem $F(x,y,z)=x^3+y^2e^z+xyz$ as core models.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## Learning goals\n",
        "\n",
        "After studying this chapter, you should be able to:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. explain why tangent planes are multivariable tangent lines;\n",
        "2. find the tangent plane to a surface $z=f(x,y)$ at a point;\n",
        "3. compute the linearization $L(x,y)$ of a function $f(x,y)$ at $(a,b)$;\n",
        "4. use linearization to estimate nearby function values;\n",
        "5. write linear approximation in gradient-dot-product form;\n",
        "6. explain the difference between partial derivatives existing and differentiability;\n",
        "7. compute total differentials and use them for error propagation;\n",
        "8. find tangent planes to level surfaces $F(x,y,z)=c$;\n",
        "9. interpret local linear models in statistics, data science, and machine learning;\n",
        "10. use Python to visualize tangent planes and approximation errors.\n",
        "\n",
        "Python resources for this chapter:\n",
        "\n",
        "- [Chapter 9 Python lab](../labs/MATH2321_Chapter09_Linear_Approximation_Tangent_Planes_and_Differentials.ipynb)\n",
        "- [Chapter 9 interactive HTML page](../htmls/chapter-09.html)\n",
        "\n",
        "## 9.1 Review: tangent lines and local linearity\n",
        "\n",
        "For a single-variable function $y=f(x)$, the tangent line at $x=a$ is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "L(x)=f(a)+f'(a)(x-a).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The tangent line is useful because when $x$ is close to $a$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(x) \\approx L(x).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The number $f'(a)$ tells how the output changes per unit change in the input. If $\\Delta x=x-a$, then\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\Delta y=f(x)-f(a) \\approx f'(a)\\Delta x.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This is the one-variable version of the multivariable formula\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\Delta z \\approx f_x(a,b)\\Delta x+f_y(a,b)\\Delta y.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The right side is linear in the input changes $\\Delta x$ and $\\Delta y$. That is why we call it a **linear approximation**.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-tip title='Local does not mean global'}\n",
        "A tangent line or tangent plane usually gives a good approximation only near the point of tangency. Far away from the point, the nonlinear curvature of the graph becomes important.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 9.2 Tangent planes to graphs $z=f(x,y)$\n",
        "\n",
        "Let $z=f(x,y)$ be differentiable near $(a,b)$, and let\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "P=(a,b,f(a,b))\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "be the point on the graph. The tangent plane at $P$ is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "z-f(a,b)=f_x(a,b)(x-a)+f_y(a,b)(y-b).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Equivalently,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "z=f(a,b)+f_x(a,b)(x-a)+f_y(a,b)(y-b).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The function on the right is the **linearization** of $f$ at $(a,b)$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "L(x,y)=f(a,b)+f_x(a,b)(x-a)+f_y(a,b)(y-b).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The approximation\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(x,y)\\approx L(x,y)\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "is called the **linear approximation** or **tangent plane approximation**.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why this is the right plane\n",
        "\n",
        "At the point $(a,b)$, the tangent plane must match three pieces of first-order information:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. the height $f(a,b)$;\n",
        "2. the slope in the $x$-direction, $f_x(a,b)$;\n",
        "3. the slope in the $y$-direction, $f_y(a,b)$.\n",
        "\n",
        "The plane\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "z=L(x,y)\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "has exactly these three properties.\n",
        "\n",
        "A useful normal vector to the tangent plane is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\langle f_x(a,b), f_y(a,b), -1\\rangle.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This comes from rewriting the tangent plane as\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_x(a,b)(x-a)+f_y(a,b)(y-b)-(z-f(a,b))=0.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "## 9.3 Worked example: tangent plane to an elliptic paraboloid\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example 9.1\n",
        "\n",
        "Find the tangent plane to\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "z=f(x,y)=3x^2+y^2\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "at the point $(1,2,7)$.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Solution\n",
        "\n",
        "First check the height:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(1,2)=3(1)^2+(2)^2=7.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Compute the partial derivatives:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_x(x,y)=6x,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "f_y(x,y)=2y.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "At $(1,2)$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_x(1,2)=6,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "f_y(1,2)=4.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Therefore the tangent plane is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "z-7=6(x-1)+4(y-2).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Solving for $z$ gives\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "z=6x+4y-7.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Thus the linearization is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "L(x,y)=6x+4y-7.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "To estimate $f(1.1,1.9)$, compute\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "L(1.1,1.9)=6(1.1)+4(1.9)-7=7.2.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The exact value is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(1.1,1.9)=3(1.1)^2+(1.9)^2=7.24.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The tangent plane gives a close approximation because $(1.1,1.9)$ is near $(1,2)$."
      ],
      "id": "dc22bf79"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "fig-width": 7,
        "fig-height": 5
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: fig-ch09-tangent-plane-paraboloid\n",
        "#| fig-cap: The graph of z=3x^2+y^2 and its tangent plane at (1,2,7).\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "x = np.linspace(0.2, 1.8, 80)\n",
        "y = np.linspace(1.2, 2.8, 80)\n",
        "X, Y = np.meshgrid(x, y)\n",
        "Z = 3*X**2 + Y**2\n",
        "L = 7 + 6*(X - 1) + 4*(Y - 2)\n",
        "\n",
        "fig = plt.figure()\n",
        "ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')\n",
        "ax.plot_surface(X, Y, Z, alpha=0.65, linewidth=0)\n",
        "ax.plot_surface(X, Y, L, alpha=0.35, linewidth=0)\n",
        "ax.scatter([1], [2], [7], s=60)\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel('$x$')\n",
        "ax.set_ylabel('$y$')\n",
        "ax.set_zlabel('$z$')\n",
        "ax.set_title('Surface and tangent plane')\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "fig-ch09-tangent-plane-paraboloid",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 9.4 Linear approximation in gradient form\n",
        "\n",
        "The linear approximation formula can be written more compactly using the gradient. Let\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\Delta x=x-a,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "\\Delta y=y-b,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "\\Delta \\mathbf{x}=\\langle \\Delta x,\\Delta y\\rangle.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Then\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(x,y)-f(a,b)\\approx \\nabla f(a,b)\\cdot \\Delta \\mathbf{x}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Equivalently,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\Delta z\\approx \\nabla f(a,b)\\cdot \\Delta \\mathbf{x}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This formula is one of the most important formulas in multivariable calculus. It says:\n",
        "\n",
        "> Near a point, the change in the output is approximately the dot product of the gradient and the input displacement.\n",
        "\n",
        "For a function $f:\\mathbb R^n\\to \\mathbb R$, the same formula is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(\\mathbf{x})\\approx f(\\mathbf{a})+\\nabla f(\\mathbf{a})\\cdot (\\mathbf{x}-\\mathbf{a}).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example 9.2\n",
        "\n",
        "Suppose\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(2,1)=13,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "\\nabla f(2,1)=\\langle 12,2\\rangle.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Estimate $f(2.1,0.9)$.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Solution\n",
        "\n",
        "The input displacement is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\Delta \\mathbf{x}=\\langle 2.1-2,0.9-1\\rangle\n",
        "=\\langle 0.1,-0.1\\rangle.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Therefore\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\Delta z\\approx \\langle 12,2\\rangle\\cdot \\langle 0.1,-0.1\\rangle\n",
        "=12(0.1)+2(-0.1)=1.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "So\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(2.1,0.9)\\approx 13+1=14.\n",
        "$$"
      ],
      "id": "81b1a2cf"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "fig-width": 6,
        "fig-height": 6
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: fig-ch09-gradient-dot-displacement\n",
        "#| fig-cap: Linear approximation uses the dot product of the gradient and the displacement vector.\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "p = np.array([2.0, 1.0])\n",
        "q = np.array([2.1, 0.9])\n",
        "grad = np.array([12.0, 2.0])\n",
        "delta = q - p\n",
        "\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
        "ax.scatter([p[0], q[0]], [p[1], q[1]], s=70)\n",
        "ax.annotate('P=(2,1)', p + np.array([-0.08, 0.03]))\n",
        "ax.annotate('Q=(2.1,0.9)', q + np.array([0.02, -0.05]))\n",
        "ax.quiver(p[0], p[1], delta[0], delta[1], angles='xy', scale_units='xy', scale=1)\n",
        "ax.quiver(p[0], p[1], 0.08*grad[0], 0.08*grad[1], angles='xy', scale_units='xy', scale=1)\n",
        "ax.set_aspect('equal', adjustable='box')\n",
        "ax.set_xlim(1.85, 3.1)\n",
        "ax.set_ylim(0.65, 1.35)\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel('$x$')\n",
        "ax.set_ylabel('$y$')\n",
        "ax.set_title('Displacement and gradient direction')\n",
        "ax.grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "fig-ch09-gradient-dot-displacement",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 9.5 Approximation error and curvature\n",
        "\n",
        "The linearization keeps only first-order information. The error comes from second-order and higher-order behavior. For the paraboloid\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(x,y)=3x^2+y^2,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "the tangent plane at $(1,2)$ is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "L(x,y)=6x+4y-7.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The error is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "E(x,y)=f(x,y)-L(x,y).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "For this example,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "E(x,y)=3(x-1)^2+(y-2)^2.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This is always nonnegative because the surface is convex and lies above its tangent plane. The error is small near $(1,2)$ and grows quadratically as we move away."
      ],
      "id": "1ed9b12a"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "fig-width": 7,
        "fig-height": 5
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: fig-ch09-linearization-error\n",
        "#| fig-cap: The linearization error is small near the base point and grows as we move away.\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "x = np.linspace(0.4, 1.6, 200)\n",
        "y = np.linspace(1.4, 2.6, 200)\n",
        "X, Y = np.meshgrid(x, y)\n",
        "f = 3*X**2 + Y**2\n",
        "L = 7 + 6*(X - 1) + 4*(Y - 2)\n",
        "E = f - L\n",
        "\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
        "cs = ax.contourf(X, Y, E, levels=20)\n",
        "fig.colorbar(cs, ax=ax, label='error f - L')\n",
        "ax.scatter([1], [2], s=60)\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel('$x$')\n",
        "ax.set_ylabel('$y$')\n",
        "ax.set_title('Error of tangent plane approximation')\n",
        "ax.set_aspect('equal', adjustable='box')\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "fig-ch09-linearization-error",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "::: {.callout-note title='Connection to Chapter 18'}\n",
        "Later, Taylor approximation will make this precise. The second-order term involves the Hessian matrix. Linear approximation is first-order Taylor approximation; quadratic approximation is second-order Taylor approximation.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 9.6 Differentiability\n",
        "\n",
        "A function $f(x,y)$ is **differentiable** at $(a,b)$ if its change can be written as a linear part plus an error that becomes negligible compared with the size of the input change.\n",
        "\n",
        "One way to state this is:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\Delta z=f_x(a,b)\\Delta x+f_y(a,b)\\Delta y+\\varepsilon_1\\Delta x+\\varepsilon_2\\Delta y,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\varepsilon_1\\to 0,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "\\varepsilon_2\\to 0\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "as $(\\Delta x,\\Delta y)\\to (0,0)$.\n",
        "\n",
        "Equivalently,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(a+\\Delta x,b+\\Delta y)=f(a,b)+f_x(a,b)\\Delta x+f_y(a,b)\\Delta y+\\text{small error}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The important idea is not just that the partial derivatives exist. The important idea is that together they produce a good linear model near the point.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-warning title='Partial derivatives alone are not enough'}\n",
        "A function may have partial derivatives at a point but fail to be differentiable there. Differentiability is stronger than the existence of coordinate-direction slopes.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "A practical sufficient condition is the following.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-tip title='Sufficient condition for differentiability'}\n",
        "If $f_x$ and $f_y$ exist near $(a,b)$ and are continuous at $(a,b)$, then $f$ is differentiable at $(a,b)$.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "This theorem is one reason continuous partial derivatives are so important. In most computational and applied examples, we verify differentiability by verifying that the partial derivatives are continuous.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 9.7 A cautionary example\n",
        "\n",
        "Consider\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(x,y)=\n",
        "\\begin{cases}\n",
        "\\dfrac{xy}{\\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}, & (x,y)\\neq (0,0),\\\\\n",
        "0, & (x,y)=(0,0).\n",
        "\\end{cases}\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "At the origin, the coordinate partial derivatives exist:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_x(0,0)=0,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "f_y(0,0)=0.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "So the candidate linearization is $L(x,y)=0$. However, along the line $y=x$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(x,x)=\\frac{x^2}{\\sqrt{2x^2}}=\\frac{|x|}{\\sqrt 2}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This is not negligible compared with the distance $\\sqrt{x^2+x^2}=\\sqrt 2|x|$. Therefore the function is not differentiable at the origin."
      ],
      "id": "73c4f92c"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "fig-width": 7,
        "fig-height": 5
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: fig-ch09-partials-not-differentiable\n",
        "#| fig-cap: A function can have coordinate partial derivatives at a point but still fail to be differentiable there.\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "x = np.linspace(-1, 1, 250)\n",
        "y = np.linspace(-1, 1, 250)\n",
        "X, Y = np.meshgrid(x, y)\n",
        "R = np.sqrt(X**2 + Y**2)\n",
        "Z = np.zeros_like(R)\n",
        "mask = R > 1e-12\n",
        "Z[mask] = X[mask]*Y[mask]/R[mask]\n",
        "\n",
        "fig, ax = plt.subplots()\n",
        "cs = ax.contourf(X, Y, Z, levels=30)\n",
        "fig.colorbar(cs, ax=ax, label='$f(x,y)$')\n",
        "ax.plot(x, x, linewidth=2)\n",
        "ax.axhline(0, linewidth=1)\n",
        "ax.axvline(0, linewidth=1)\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel('$x$')\n",
        "ax.set_ylabel('$y$')\n",
        "ax.set_title('Behavior near the origin')\n",
        "ax.set_aspect('equal', adjustable='box')\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "fig-ch09-partials-not-differentiable",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 9.8 Tangent planes to level surfaces\n",
        "\n",
        "Many important surfaces are not given as graphs $z=f(x,y)$. Instead, they are given implicitly as level surfaces\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "F(x,y,z)=c.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Suppose\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "P=(a,b,c_0)\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "is a point on the level surface. If\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\nabla F(P)\\neq \\mathbf{0},\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "then the gradient vector is normal to the level surface at $P$. Therefore the tangent plane is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\nabla F(P)\\cdot \\langle x-a,y-b,z-c_0\\rangle=0.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "In coordinates, if\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\nabla F(P)=\\langle F_x(P),F_y(P),F_z(P)\\rangle,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "then the tangent plane is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "F_x(P)(x-a)+F_y(P)(y-b)+F_z(P)(z-c_0)=0.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why the gradient is normal\n",
        "\n",
        "If a curve $\\mathbf r(t)$ lies on the level surface, then\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "F(\\mathbf r(t))=c.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Differentiating with respect to $t$ gives\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\nabla F(\\mathbf r(t))\\cdot \\mathbf r'(t)=0.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Thus the gradient is perpendicular to every tangent direction $\\mathbf r'(t)$ on the surface.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 9.9 Worked example: linearization and tangent plane to a level surface\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example 9.3\n",
        "\n",
        "Let\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "F(x,y,z)=x^3+y^2e^z+xyz\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "and let\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "P=(1,2,0).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "1. Find the linearization of $F$ at $P$.\n",
        "2. Estimate $F(1.1,1.9,0)$ using the linearization.\n",
        "3. Find the tangent plane to the level surface through $P$.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Solution\n",
        "\n",
        "First evaluate the function:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "F(1,2,0)=1^3+2^2e^0+1\\cdot 2\\cdot 0=5.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Compute the partial derivatives:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "F_x=3x^2+yz,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "F_y=2ye^z+xz,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "F_z=y^2e^z+xy.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "At $P=(1,2,0)$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "F_x(P)=3,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "F_y(P)=4,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "F_z(P)=6.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "So the linearization is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "L(x,y,z)=F(P)+F_x(P)(x-1)+F_y(P)(y-2)+F_z(P)(z-0).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Therefore\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "L(x,y,z)=5+3(x-1)+4(y-2)+6z.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "After simplifying,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "L(x,y,z)=3x+4y+6z-6.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Now estimate:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "F(1.1,1.9,0)\\approx L(1.1,1.9,0)=3(1.1)+4(1.9)-6=4.9.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The level surface through $P$ is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "F(x,y,z)=5.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Its tangent plane is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "3(x-1)+4(y-2)+6z=0.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Equivalently,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "3x+4y+6z-11=0.\n",
        "$$"
      ],
      "id": "b4919fb1"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "fig-width": 7,
        "fig-height": 5
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: fig-ch09-level-surface-tangent-plane\n",
        "#| fig-cap: A tangent plane to the level surface F(x,y,z)=5 near P=(1,2,0).\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "# Solve the tangent plane for z: 3(x-1)+4(y-2)+6z=0\n",
        "x = np.linspace(0.6, 1.4, 80)\n",
        "y = np.linspace(1.5, 2.5, 80)\n",
        "X, Y = np.meshgrid(x, y)\n",
        "Zplane = -(3*(X - 1) + 4*(Y - 2))/6\n",
        "\n",
        "# Approximate the level surface locally by solving F(x,y,z)=5 with Newton iterations in z.\n",
        "def F(x, y, z):\n",
        "    return x**3 + y**2*np.exp(z) + x*y*z\n",
        "\n",
        "Z = Zplane.copy()\n",
        "for _ in range(6):\n",
        "    dFdz = Y**2*np.exp(Z) + X*Y\n",
        "    Z = Z - (F(X, Y, Z) - 5)/dFdz\n",
        "\n",
        "fig = plt.figure()\n",
        "ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')\n",
        "ax.plot_surface(X, Y, Z, alpha=0.65, linewidth=0)\n",
        "ax.plot_surface(X, Y, Zplane, alpha=0.35, linewidth=0)\n",
        "ax.scatter([1], [2], [0], s=60)\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel('$x$')\n",
        "ax.set_ylabel('$y$')\n",
        "ax.set_zlabel('$z$')\n",
        "ax.set_title('Level surface and tangent plane')\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ],
      "id": "fig-ch09-level-surface-tangent-plane",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 9.10 Total differentials\n",
        "\n",
        "For a differentiable function $z=f(x,y)$, define $dx$ and $dy$ as independent small changes in the input variables. The **total differential** is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "dz=f_x(x,y)\\,dx+f_y(x,y)\\,dy.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "At a specific point $(a,b)$, this becomes\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "dz=f_x(a,b)\\,dx+f_y(a,b)\\,dy.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The differential is the linear approximation to the actual change:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\Delta z\\approx dz.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "For a function of three variables,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "w=f(x,y,z),\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "the total differential is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "dw=f_x\\,dx+f_y\\,dy+f_z\\,dz.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "More generally, for $f:\\mathbb R^n\\to \\mathbb R$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "df=\\nabla f(\\mathbf{x})\\cdot d\\mathbf{x}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-note title='Why differentials matter'}\n",
        "Deltas such as $\\Delta x$ and $\\Delta y$ represent actual changes. Differentials such as $dx$ and $dy$ are independent input changes used in the linear model. The differential $dz$ is the predicted output change from the tangent plane.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 9.11 Error propagation and sensitivity analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "In applied problems, inputs are often measured with error. Linear approximation allows us to estimate how input error affects output error.\n",
        "\n",
        "Suppose\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "z=f(x,y)\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "and the possible measurement errors are\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "|dx|\\leq \\epsilon_x,\n",
        "\\qquad\n",
        "|dy|\\leq \\epsilon_y.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Then a first-order estimate for the output error is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "|dz|\\leq |f_x(x,y)|\\epsilon_x+|f_y(x,y)|\\epsilon_y.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This is a deterministic worst-case estimate.\n",
        "\n",
        "If instead $dx$ and $dy$ are random errors with covariance matrix $\\Sigma$, then the approximate variance of the output is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\operatorname{Var}(df)\\approx \\nabla f(\\mathbf{x})^T\\Sigma\\nabla f(\\mathbf{x}).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This is the core idea behind the **delta method** in statistics.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Example 9.4: volume of a cylinder\n",
        "\n",
        "The volume of a cylinder is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "V(r,h)=\\pi r^2h.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The differential is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "dV=2\\pi rh\\,dr+\\pi r^2\\,dh.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "At $r=3$ and $h=10$,\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "dV=60\\pi\\,dr+9\\pi\\,dh.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "If $dr=0.02$ and $dh=-0.05$, then\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "dV\\approx 60\\pi(0.02)+9\\pi(-0.05)=0.75\\pi.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "So the predicted volume change is approximately\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "0.75\\pi\\approx 2.36.\n",
        "$$"
      ],
      "id": "7efda859"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "fig-width": 7,
        "fig-height": 5
