        "## 9.13 Numerical linearization from finite differences\n",
        "\n",
        "In real applications, we may not have a symbolic formula for the gradient. We may only have a black-box function that can be evaluated. Then we can approximate the gradient numerically.\n",
        "\n",
        "For a function $f(x,y)$, central finite differences give\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_x(a,b)\\approx \\frac{f(a+h,b)-f(a-h,b)}{2h},\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f_y(a,b)\\approx \\frac{f(a,b+h)-f(a,b-h)}{2h}.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Then the numerical linearization is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "L(x,y)=f(a,b)+\\widehat f_x(a,b)(x-a)+\\widehat f_y(a,b)(y-b).\n",
        "$$"
      ],
      "id": "154b4ef7"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "fig-width": 7,
        "fig-height": 5
      },
      "source": [
        "#| label: fig-ch09-finite-difference-linearization\n",
        "#| fig-cap: Finite differences can approximate the gradient used in a local linear model.\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "def f(x, y):\n",
        "    return np.sin(x*y) + 0.2*x**2 - 0.1*y**3\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "a, b = 1.0, 0.8\n",
        "h = 1e-4\n",
        "fx_hat = (f(a + h, b) - f(a - h, b))/(2*h)\n",
        "fy_hat = (f(a, b + h) - f(a, b - h))/(2*h)\n",
        "\n",
        "x = np.linspace(0.5, 1.5, 120)\n",
        "y = np.linspace(0.3, 1.3, 120)\n",
        "X, Y = np.meshgrid(x, y)\n",
        "Z = f(X, Y)\n",
        "L = f(a, b) + fx_hat*(X - a) + fy_hat*(Y - b)\n",
        "\n",
        "fig = plt.figure()\n",
        "ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')\n",
        "ax.plot_surface(X, Y, Z, alpha=0.65, linewidth=0)\n",
        "ax.plot_surface(X, Y, L, alpha=0.35, linewidth=0)\n",
        "ax.scatter([a], [b], [f(a,b)], s=60)\n",
        "ax.set_xlabel('$x$')\n",
        "ax.set_ylabel('$y$')\n",
        "ax.set_zlabel('$z$')\n",
        "ax.set_title('Numerical tangent plane')\n",
        "plt.show()\n",
        "\n",
        "print('finite-difference gradient:', (fx_hat, fy_hat))"
      ],
      "id": "fig-ch09-finite-difference-linearization",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## 9.14 Vector-valued and matrix viewpoints\n",
        "\n",
        "The scalar-valued formula\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(\\mathbf{x})\\approx f(\\mathbf{a})+\\nabla f(\\mathbf{a})\\cdot(\\mathbf{x}-\\mathbf{a})\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "has a natural extension to vector-valued functions. If\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\mathbf{F}:\\mathbb R^n\\to \\mathbb R^m,\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "then the best first-order approximation is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\mathbf{F}(\\mathbf{x})\\approx \\mathbf{F}(\\mathbf{a})+J_{\\mathbf{F}}(\\mathbf{a})(\\mathbf{x}-\\mathbf{a}),\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where $J_{\\mathbf{F}}(\\mathbf{a})$ is the **Jacobian matrix**. This is the subject of the next chapter.\n",
        "\n",
        "For now, the key idea is that derivatives in many variables are linear maps. The gradient-dot-product formula is the scalar-output version of this principle.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 9.15 Common mistakes\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-warning title='Mistake 1: using the wrong base point'}\n",
        "The tangent plane formula must use the point of tangency $(a,b)$ and the height $f(a,b)$. Do not plug in the nearby point where you want the estimate.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-warning title='Mistake 2: mixing up graph surfaces and level surfaces'}\n",
        "For a graph $z=f(x,y)$, use\n",
        "$$\n",
        "z-f(a,b)=f_x(a,b)(x-a)+f_y(a,b)(y-b).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "For a level surface $F(x,y,z)=c$, use\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\nabla F(P)\\cdot \\langle x-a,y-b,z-c_0\\rangle=0.\n",
        "$$\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-warning title='Mistake 3: thinking partial derivatives guarantee differentiability'}\n",
        "Partial derivatives measure coordinate-direction slopes. Differentiability means there is a good linear approximation in all directions at once.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## 9.16 Summary of key formulas\n",
        "\n",
        "For $z=f(x,y)$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "L(x,y)=f(a,b)+f_x(a,b)(x-a)+f_y(a,b)(y-b).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Tangent plane to $z=f(x,y)$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "z-f(a,b)=f_x(a,b)(x-a)+f_y(a,b)(y-b).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Gradient form:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(x,y)-f(a,b)\\approx \\nabla f(a,b)\\cdot \\langle x-a,y-b\\rangle.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Total differential:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "dz=f_x\\,dx+f_y\\,dy.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "For $f:\\mathbb R^n\\to \\mathbb R$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "f(\\mathbf{x})\\approx f(\\mathbf{a})+\\nabla f(\\mathbf{a})\\cdot(\\mathbf{x}-\\mathbf{a}).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Tangent plane to $F(x,y,z)=c$ at $P=(a,b,c_0)$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "F_x(P)(x-a)+F_y(P)(y-b)+F_z(P)(z-c_0)=0.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "## 9.17 Practice problems\n",
        "\n",
        "### Conceptual problems\n",
        "\n",
        "1. In your own words, explain why a tangent plane is a local linear model.\n",
        "2. What information does the tangent plane to $z=f(x,y)$ match at the base point?\n",
        "3. Explain why the gradient of $F$ is normal to the level surface $F(x,y,z)=c$.\n",
        "4. Explain the difference between $\\Delta z$ and $dz$.\n",
        "5. Why can a function have partial derivatives but fail to be differentiable?\n",
        "\n",
        "### Skill problems\n",
        "\n",
        "6. Find the tangent plane to $z=x^2+3y^2$ at $(1,-1,4)$.\n",
        "7. Find the linearization of $f(x,y)=e^{xy}+x^2y$ at $(1,0)$.\n",
        "8. Use a linear approximation to estimate $\\sqrt{(4.1)^2+(2.9)^2}$.\n",
        "9. Suppose $f(3,2)=10$ and $\\nabla f(3,2)=\\langle -2,5\\rangle$. Estimate $f(2.9,2.2)$.\n",
        "10. Find $dz$ for $z=x^2\\sin y+e^{xy}$.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Level-surface problems\n",
        "\n",
        "11. Find the tangent plane to $x^2+y^2+z^2=14$ at $(1,2,3)$.\n",
        "12. Find the tangent plane to $x^3+y^2e^z+xyz=5$ at $(1,2,0)$.\n",
        "13. Find the tangent plane to $\\ln(x+y+z)=0$ at $(1,0,0)$.\n",
        "14. Find a normal vector to the level surface $F(x,y,z)=x^2y+yz^2$ at $(1,2,1)$.\n",
        "15. Find the linearization of $F(x,y,z)=x^2+y^2+z^2$ at $(1,2,2)$.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Applied and computational problems\n",
        "\n",
        "16. The volume of a rectangular box is $V=xyz$. Use differentials to estimate the change in volume when $(x,y,z)=(10,5,2)$ changes by $(dx,dy,dz)=(0.1,-0.05,0.02)$.\n",
        "17. The BMI formula is $B(W,H)=703W/H^2$, where $W$ is weight in pounds and $H$ is height in inches. Use differentials to estimate how small errors in $W$ and $H$ affect BMI.\n",
        "18. For $f(x,y)=\\sin(xy)+x^2$, use finite differences to estimate the tangent plane at $(1,1)$.\n",
        "19. For a prediction model $p(\\beta_0,\\beta_1)=1/(1+e^{-(\\beta_0+2\\beta_1)})$, find the linearization at $(0,1)$.\n",
        "20. Choose a nonlinear function of two variables, plot the surface and tangent plane in Python, and describe where the approximation is accurate.\n",
        "\n",
        "## 9.18 Python lab and interactive page\n",
        "\n",
        "The Python lab for this chapter should ask students to build local linear models from symbolic formulas, numerical finite differences, and data-based approximations.\n",
        "\n",
        "Recommended lab activities:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. visualize the surface $z=3x^2+y^2$ and its tangent plane at $(1,2)$;\n",
        "2. compare exact values with linearized values on a grid;\n",
        "3. compute and visualize approximation error;\n",
        "4. estimate gradients numerically using finite differences;\n",
        "5. find tangent planes to level surfaces using gradients;\n",
        "6. simulate error propagation for measurement uncertainty;\n",
        "7. explore local linearization of a logistic probability model.\n",
        "\n",
        "- Notebook lab: [MATH2321_Chapter09_Linear_Approximation_Tangent_Planes_and_Differentials.ipynb](../labs/MATH2321_Chapter09_Linear_Approximation_Tangent_Planes_and_Differentials.ipynb)\n",
        "- Interactive HTML page: [Chapter 09 interactive page](../htmls/chapter-09.html)\n",
        "\n",
        "## Chapter summary\n",
        "\n",
        "Linear approximation is the first major synthesis point of multivariable calculus. Partial derivatives become a gradient. The gradient becomes a local linear model. The local linear model becomes a tangent plane, a differential, a sensitivity estimate, and a computational approximation.\n",
        "\n",
        "For graphs $z=f(x,y)$, the tangent plane is\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "z=f(a,b)+f_x(a,b)(x-a)+f_y(a,b)(y-b).\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "For level surfaces $F(x,y,z)=c$, the tangent plane is determined by the normal vector $\\nabla F(P)$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\\nabla F(P)\\cdot(\\mathbf{x}-P)=0.\n",
        "$$\n",
        "\n",
        "In applied mathematics and statistics, this chapter is the foundation for error propagation, the delta method, local optimization, and first-order approximation of nonlinear models. In machine learning and AI, it is the idea behind using gradients to approximate and improve complicated models one small step at a time."
